docs.abstract: Major companies are often wary of conflict, especially in a polarized time. But some are now taking a stand on racial injustice and police violence.
docs.snippet: Major companies are often wary of conflict, especially in a polarized time. But some are now taking a stand on racial injustice and police violence.
docs.lead_paragraph: As tensions flared around the country after George Floyd’s death under a policeman’s knee, protesters received support from an unexpected corner: corporate America.

headline.main: Corporate Voices Get Behind ‘Black Lives Matter’ Cause
headline.print_headline: More Corporate Voices, Typically Shy on Issues, Speak Out on Racism

docs.abstract: The president spent Sunday out of sight, berating opponents on Twitter, even as some of his campaign advisers were recommending that he deliver a televised address to an anxious nation.
docs.snippet: The president spent Sunday out of sight, berating opponents on Twitter, even as some of his campaign advisers were recommending that he deliver a televised address to an anxious nation.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Inside the White House, the mood was bristling with tension. Hundreds of protesters were gathering outside the gates, shouting curses at President Trump and in some cases throwing bricks and bottles. Nervous for his safety, Secret Service agents abruptly rushed the president to the underground bunker used in the past during terrorist attacks.

headline.main: As Protests and Violence Spill Over, Trump Shrinks Back
headline.print_headline: Trump Offers No Calming Words As Tumult Reaches White House

docs.abstract: Historically speaking, when white people are afraid, it is usually people of color who get hurt.
docs.snippet: Historically speaking, when white people are afraid, it is usually people of color who get hurt.
docs.lead_paragraph: The symbolism is almost too much to bear. The antagonist stares down the barrel of the camera, removing her surgical face mask at the same moment she takes off her figurative mask and offers the audience a glimpse into what lies beneath. The woman, Amy Cooper, points her finger at the stranger behind the camera, Christian Cooper, to demand that he stop filming her. When he refuses, she threatens to call the police and then immediately acts on her threat.

headline.main: A White Damsel Leveraged Racial Power and Failed

docs.abstract: President Trump’s predecessors took different approaches when responding — or not responding — to police killings or assaults of black men. But they never threatened violence against protesters.
docs.snippet: President Trump’s predecessors took different approaches when responding — or not responding — to police killings or assaults of black men. But they never threatened violence against protesters.
docs.lead_paragraph: It is a bleak reality of American history that each of the past four presidents faced the same crisis President Trump is facing now: The police just killed or seriously injured a black man, and the city where it happened is reeling with grief and rage.

headline.main: Past Presidents Faced Police Brutality and Protests. They Handled It Differently.

docs.lead_paragraph: Myan Mode, a garment factory on the outskirts of Yangon, Myanmar, produces men’s jackets, women’s blazers and coats for Western fashion companies like Mango and Zara. Since the start of the coronavirus pandemic, it has seen a decrease in orders from international retailers.

headline.main: Union Garment Workers Fear ‘an Opportunity to Get Rid of Us’

docs.abstract: Walter Johnson’s book about the city, “The Broken Heart of America,” shows how troubled St. Louis has been from the start, even amid signs of hope.
docs.snippet: Walter Johnson’s book about the city, “The Broken Heart of America,” shows how troubled St. Louis has been from the start, even amid signs of hope.
docs.lead_paragraph: A century ago, W.E.B. Du Bois wrote about St. Louis, a city that “sprawls where mighty rivers meet,” and offered an autopsy of a tragedy. In the summer of 1917, after a labor dispute at an aluminum plant, black residents of East St. Louis were chased down, strung up, beaten, burned and shot. Their white neighbors had turned on them with a viciousness that was gratuitous and grotesque — a cruelty too extravagant to be understood as a matter of mere survival. “It was not that the white American worker was threatened with starvation,” Du Bois wrote, pointing to the booming wartime economy, “but it was what was, after all, a more important question — whether or not he should lose his front-room and Victrola and even the dream of a Ford car.”

headline.main: Rivers Merge in St. Louis. So Do Racism, Violence and Exclusion.
headline.print_headline: Racism and Inequality Where the Rivers Meet

docs.abstract: Nikil Saval wants to bring more democratic socialism to Philadelphia, as part of a leftist wave in American electoral politics.
docs.snippet: Nikil Saval wants to bring more democratic socialism to Philadelphia, as part of a leftist wave in American electoral politics.
docs.lead_paragraph: Nikil Saval is a socialist candidate running for State Senate in Pennsylvania’s 1st district, which encompasses a huge swath of Philadelphia. He used to edit the literary and political magazine N+1, which is to say that he is more bookish than your standard elected-office-seeker. This occasionally gets in his way.

headline.print_headline: Socialist in Run for Philadelphia ‘Safe Seat’

docs.abstract: Across the country, mayors, public health experts and other officials worry that even though many protesters are wearing masks, the risk of new coronavirus cases will increase as thousands gather.
docs.snippet: Across the country, mayors, public health experts and other officials worry that even though many protesters are wearing masks, the risk of new coronavirus cases will increase as thousands gather.
docs.lead_paragraph: Mass protests against police brutality that have brought thousands of people out of their homes and onto the streets in cities across America are raising the specter of new coronavirus outbreaks, prompting political leaders, physicians and public health experts to warn that the crowds could cause a surge in cases.

headline.main: Will Protests Set Off a Second Viral Wave?
headline.print_headline: Mass Protests Bring Fear of Hot Spots
